A humble reworking of Moonjammy's excellent designs, optimised for stackable printing.

Love printing little dudes but hate having to get up every hour to scrape off your build plate, waste good resin in your wash station, and restart the print? Then here's the new easy-to-use stacking solution you've been waiting for! Stack small objects vertically to fit into your print schedule, or efficiently fill left over build plate volume when printing taller objects.

Including:
- **Galactic Crusader Infantry in Heavy Siege Armour** with a choice of Boxing Gloves or Hedge Trimmers and a selection of heavy weaponry
- Arranged in pre-built stacks of 12, 18 and 24.
- Raw components and a guide for creating custom stacks

**Scale and Sizing:**
The Galactic Crusaders in this pack have been resized to 105%.
This makes the average Galactic Crusader ~9.5mm tall (varying based on pose and armour style), and the base plugs 6.16x1.31mm.

A humble reworking of the very concept of a raft, optimised for vertical printing.

Floating Rafts are small self-supporting structures that establish platforms parallel with but above the build plate.
This allows you to take models that have been supported for standard printing (or even auto-supported) and quickly convert them into stackable designs with minimal effort!
While individually small, Floating Rafts can be combined side by side to form wider rafts, or even mirrored front-to-back to create much larger rafts suitable for small scale vehicles, or larger scale components like helmets, shoulder pads and weapons for 28mm models.

**Wait, what's the point in stacking prints? Isn't that just a waste of resin?**

Stacking prints incurs a small amount of additional resin use, but brings a number of big advantages:
- You can scale a large number of small print jobs up into bigger print jobs. i.e. You can run one overnight 8h print instead of six or seven 1h30m prints, each of which need to be scraped off the build plate, cleaned, etc, before they can be re-run.
- You can scale small objects to fit in with the largest objects on your build plate. i.e. If you are printing a 28mm vehicle with parts that are 80mm tall, arrange smaller parts in 80mm stacks to make best use of a long print. This allows you to use small amounts of leftover build plate space to print large numbers of components!
- You can _slightly_ decrease overall print times, as stacked components can be kept very close to their floating rafts.


**How do I use this?**

Take any traditionally supported (or even auto-supported!) object that fits within an area you are able to create with Floating Rafts.

1.a. Replace the existing raft with platform made from Floating rafts.
1.b. Optionally shorten the existing supports to 1-2mm. Traditionally objects are raised 5mm above the build plate to avoid raft collision, but that's not necessary when you're up in the stacks!
_(I typically use Blender for this, but you could use subtraction in Windows 3D Builder or a simple Planar Cut in your slicer!)_
2. Stack your objects on central supports.
_(I embed the floating rafts in central support pillars, but for peak resin efficiency, why not try embedding the rafts in something you are planning to print anyway, like the undersides of bases!)_
3. Print!


**Okay, that's great, but where the models at?**

Don't worry, I'll be sharing a number of packs with small-scale (and maybe not so small scale) models I worked on while experimenting with this process, which should give you some useful models to print and ideas for how to use this concept.

All your sponson needs, all in one place!

A central collection so I don't have to update a half dozen packs when modifying the sponsons, and the Universal Sponson Pin needed for the Magnetic Sponson System.

**Wait a minute, Magnetic Sponson System?**

The Magnetic Sponson System is an easy way to swap out sponson weapons. Want to change up loadouts between battles, or need to replace a snapped barrel? Just slide the old sponsons out and new ones in!

Each pin has slots for a normal sponson weapon and a 2x1mm neodymium magnet.

The pins are symmetrical, so there is no need to mirror them. Just remember the rivets point backwards, and make sure to decide on which polarity to use for the left and right pins!

**Note:** This is currently compatible with the Pred-8R, SIG-RN, and Crete-S packs.

A slightly unhinged reworking of Moonjammy's excellent design, optimised for _crazy_ printing!

A new concept for creating simple, stackable supports for Epic scale infantry! Use the supplied STLs or easily create blocks of infantry in any arbitrary width and height simply by copying strips in Lychee and moving them vertically, no additional fine-tuning required!

Streamline your games of Legions Imperialis (or Epic!) with these X-Wing-style order dials!
Just add two 3x2mm neodymium magnets and get scheming!*

If other people like these as much as I do, I'll release a full range, covering other games, and fancy designs to suit various factions and armies.
Let me know how you get on printing these, if you run into any problems, or have any suggestions for making them better!


**How should I print these?**

These dials are supported for easy and high-quality vertical printing on a resin printer.
Unsupported versions are included in case this doesn't suit you.

Aligned vertically, layer height is more important for fine detail than your printer's XY resolution, so these designs should print nicely even on older printers! I recommend using a 0.03mm layer height.

**How should I remove these weird supports?**

Like other supports, warm them up with some warm water or a heat gun before removal. Wiggle the supports back and forth and they should pop off.

In most cases this should leave next to no support marks, but if a small amount of material is left on the disc, rub them gently with some sandpaper, or scrape them with a knife/mouldline remover.

**Why are there 5 versions of the lower discs? Aren't they exactly the same?**

This is to prevent any mentats or Alpha Legion infiltrators you happen to play against from trying to predict your orders by analysing icon or support mark orientation!

**Any painting tips?**

Option 1: Paint the dials and use a pinwash to pick out the symbols and text. Oil washes work great for this!

Option 2: Paint the dials and drybrush/overbrush the raised surfaces with another colour, leaving your original colour in the recesses.

**Any tips for reducing wear and tear?**

These things are going to get handled, tossed about and rubbed together over the course of a game!

I recommend giving your paint plenty of time to fully dry unjoined before use, and to apply a good coat of varnish!

**Are you going to make a version for my favourite army/game system?**

Yep, I've already designed dials for other games like Epic, Battlefleet Gothic and Aeronautica Imperialis, and themes for a number of popular armies. If the feedback for this pack is good, I'll release others in due course!
